Source: Associated Press report, Fri 27 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://www.ljworld.com/section/stateregional/story/136695>

Kansas: Presence of West Nile Virus-positive Mosquitoes Confirmed
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Heath officials have confirmed the presence of West Nile virus in
mosquitoes from Crawford County. "We expected to see West Nile virus in the
state again this year, so this is no surprise, nor is it a reason to
panic," Dr. Gail Hansen, the state public health veterinarian, said
Thursday. "We're looking harder and earlier than we did last year."
Kansas began capturing birds and mosquitoes on 20 May 2003 and testing them
for West Nile virus. The Crawford County sample was taken on 28 May 2002,
and 16 sites are being sampled statewide. Last year, West Nile was first
confirmed in July, Hansen said. Unlike the mosquitoes that carry West Nile
on the East Coast and prefer to bite birds, Hansen said the Midwest
mosquitoes will bite bird, horse or human.
West Nile virus first arrived in Kansas last year, with 22 human cases and
794 cases found in horses and mules. More than 300 birds were tested.
Animal health officials have been encouraging owners to vaccinate horses,
something that can be done with a regular battery of shots.
[By John Milburn]
