Source: US Geological Survey, West Nile Virus National and State Maps 2003,
Wed 25 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://westnilemaps.usgs.gov/>

USGS Surveillance Update, as of Wed 25 Jun 2003
-----------------------------------------------
The national and state maps compiled by the USGS reflect information for
the 2003 West Nile virus reporting season that has been submitted and
verified to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) up to Wed
25 Jun 2003.
The surveillance maps posted on <http://westnilemaps.usgs.gov> are created
from data contained in CDC's ArboNET surveillance database. The maps
portray summaries of West Nile virus-positive surveillance data reported to
the CDC by cooperating health departments and verified to ArboNET. In
addition, maps for 2 surveillance categories (avians and mosquitoes) will
portray counties that have done "testing" of samples for WNV.
Discrepancies noted between these data and data presented from other
sources reflect local variations in reporting policies and procedures. It
is not unusual for cases to be announced in other media before being
reported and verified in ArboNET.
The following information is a synopsis of the results of West Nile virus
surveillance listed according to state. The original USGS maps further
locate both positive and negative surveillance reports by county. (The data
are provisional and may be subject to revision.)
Birds
-----
29 states are conducting surveillance with 23 states reporting cumulative
positive test results as follows: Alabama (5), Colorado (1), Florida (5),
Georgia (9), Illinois (2), Indiana (3) Iowa (4), Kentucky (0), Louisiana
(38), Michigan (6), Mississippi (3), Missouri (1), New Hampshire (0),
Nebraska (1) New Jersey (1), New York (1), North Carolina (3), North Dakota
(2), Ohio (4), Oregon (0), Pennsylvania (1), South Carolina (3), South
Dakota (0), Tennessee (4), Texas (7), Utah (0), Virginia (5), Washington
(0), Wyoming (1).

Mosquitoes
----------
11 states are conducting surveillance with 4 states reporting cumulative
positive results as follows: Colorado (0), Connecticut (0), Georgia (2),
Indiana (2), New Hampshire (0), New Jersey (1), North Carolina (0),
Pennsylvania (0), South Dakota (0), Texas (16), Utah (0).

Sentinel Flocks
---------------
3 states are conducting surveillance, with all 3 reporting cumulative
positive test results as follows: Florida (37), North Carolina (1), South
Dakota (9).

Veterinary
----------
Ten states are conducting surveillance and all 10 are reporting cumulative
positive test results [presumed to be equines] as follows: Alabama (1),
Arkansas (1), Georgia (1), Kentucky (1), Missouri (1),Minnesota (1), North
Dakota (1), Texas (4), Wisconsin (1), Wyoming (3).

Human
-----
There are no confirmed reports of surveillance activity or positive test
results from any state. [A suspected case of human infection in Washington
state (see: West Nile virus, human - USA (Washington): suspected
20030601.1334) has not been confirmed. Another suspected case was reported
from South Carolina on 15 Jun 2003 and confirmation is still pending (see:
West Nile virus, human - USA (SC) 20030615.1480). - Mod.CP]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Since the previous report dated 18 Jun 2003 the number of states carrying
out surveillance of wild birds has increased by 3 to 29. West Nile
virus-positive birds have been reported from 23 states, with positive
results reported from Missouri, Texas and Virginia for the first time. The
number of states reporting West Nile virus positive equines has increased
by two (Missouri and Texas). Four of the 11 states conducting surveillance
of mosquitoes have reported West Nile virus positive results (Georgia,
Indiana, New Jersey, and for the first time Texas). The number of states
reporting surveillance of sentinel flocks has increased from two to three,
with all three states reporting positive results. No human cases of West
Nile virus infection have been confirmed anywhere in the United States;
confirmation of a suspected case in South Carolina is still awaited. - Mod.CP]
